The paper deals with clustering and learning mixture models, which are topics typically studied in the machine learning and data science communities. The use of sum-of-squares norms and the Sum-of-Squares algorithm suggests a connection to optimization and convex programming, which are often studied in the theoretical computer science community. Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.IT (Information Theory) are the most likely categories. The paper also involves the analysis of probability distributions, which suggests a connection to statistics and probability theory, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.SD (Systems and Control) likely categories as well. Finally, the use of algorithms and upper bounds on computational complexity suggests a connection to numerical analysis and optimization, making cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) a possible category as well.
